&gt; Can anyone give me some advice on the following...
&gt; 
&gt; I&#39;m attempting to define REST-style interface for a system 
delivering
&gt; genomic map data.
&gt; 
&gt; Central to my design is the possibility of maps nesting one within
&gt; the other. Thus a map is, potentially, a composite of other maps.
&gt; Furthermore there may be many levels of nesting.  My question is, 
how
&gt; can traversal up an down this hierarchy be carried out in a REST-ful
&gt; manner? To illustrate:
&gt; 
&gt; http://bioinformatics/Map - returns details list of all maps
&gt; 
&gt; &lt;Maps&gt;
&gt;       &lt;Map href=&quot;http://bioinformatics/Map/1&quot;&gt;
&gt;             &lt;label&gt;Chromosome 1&lt;/label&gt;
&gt;             &lt;locations
&gt; href=&quot;http://bioinformatics/Map/1/Location&quot;/&gt;
&gt;       &lt;/Map&gt;
&gt;       ... thousands of Map nodes ...
&gt;       &lt;Map href=&quot;http://bioinformatics/Map/123&quot;&gt;
&gt;             &lt;label&gt;Chromosome Z&lt;/label&gt;
&gt;             &lt;locations
&gt; href=&quot;http://bioinformatics/Map/1/Location&quot;/&gt;
&gt;       &lt;/Map&gt;
&gt; &lt;/Maps&gt;
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; http://bioinformatics/Map/123 - returns a specific map
&gt; &lt;Map href=&quot;http://bioinformatics/Map/123&quot;&gt;
&gt;       &lt;label&gt;Clone Z&lt;/label&gt;
&gt;       &lt;locations href=&quot;http://bioinformatics/Map/123/Location&quot;/&gt;
&gt; &lt;/Map&gt;
&gt; 
&gt; Let&#39;s suppose that http://bioinformatics/Map/1 contains other maps
&gt; (e.g. http://bioinformatics/Map/123). At present the way to retrieve
&gt; a list of the Maps contained by http://bioinformatics/Map/1 is to
&gt; issue a GET to http://bioinformatics/Map/1/Location. This returns a
&gt; list of positional Locations on the map (i.e coordinates). Embedded
&gt; within these locations are links to the parent map and the mappable
&gt; (i.e. the Map located at this position):
&gt; 
&gt; &lt;Locations&gt;
&gt;       &lt;Location href=&quot;...&quot;&gt;
&gt;             ....
&gt;       &lt;Location&gt;
&gt;       .... thousands of Location nodes ...
&gt;       &lt;Location href=&quot;http://bioinformatics/Map/1/Location/10&quot;&gt;
&gt;             &lt;position&gt;0.2&lt;/position&gt;
&gt;             &lt;map href=&quot;http://bioinformatics/Map/1&quot;/&gt;
&gt;             &lt;mappable href=&quot;http://bioinformatics/Map/123&quot;/&gt;
&gt;       &lt;/Location&gt;
&gt; &lt;/Locations&gt;
&gt; 
&gt; Using the links provided in a Location node it should be possible to
&gt; traverse the graph of Maps.
&gt; 
&gt; To my mind this is consistent with the REST-ful idea of gradually
&gt; revealing data. Applications wishing to use the data should 
certainly
&gt; be relatively simple to write and the consistency of the interface
&gt; appeals to me. However, this scheme has the disadvantage of,
&gt; potentially, requiring many GET requests to traverse the graph. This
&gt; is mainly because the &#39;hierarchy&#39; is not a simple tree or forest - a
&gt; map be contained by more than one map. While mutliple GET&#39;s 
shouldn&#39;t
&gt; be an issue for any client keeping a connection to the server open,
&gt; I&#39;d like to avoid any such requirement. Thus, I&#39;d like to extend the
&gt; interface such that it is possible to traverse the graph of Maps,
&gt; bypassing the intermediate step of accessing Locations (the Location
&gt; data may not be of much interest to a client in any case). Is there
&gt; any sensible way to represent such a traversal? So far I&#39;ve thought
&gt; of defining two new resources, Maps ( = Containers) and Mappables ( 
=
&gt; Contents), to make such traversal possible. By specifying in the URI
&gt; the resource to which movement should be relative, traversal up or
&gt; down the hierarchy should be possible. For example:
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; http://bionformatics/Maps/Map/123  - would return a list of Maps 
that
&gt; contain http://bioinformatics/Map/123.
&gt; 
&gt; and
&gt; 
&gt; http://bioinformatics/Mappables/Map/1 - would return a list of all
&gt; the Maps contained by http://bioinformatics/Map/1
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; Does this scheme make sense? Although it seems distinctly un-REST
&gt; like, it does allow me to do what I want to do. Mmmm... should I 
even
&gt; want to do what I want to do?
